**In TypeScript, you can specify a union type to represent multiple possible values.** However, if you know that a value will only have one specific type in practice, you can use the `as` operator to **cast** it to that type.

### Example

Consider the following code:
```typescript
let value: string | number;

// Assign a string value
value = "Hello, world!";
console.log(typeof value); // "string"

// Assign a number value
value = 42;
console.log(typeof value); // "number"
```

In this example, `value` can be either a `string` or a `number`. However, if you know that `value` will always be a `string`, you can use the `as` operator to cast it:
```typescript
let value: string | number;

// Assign a string value
value = "Hello, world!";
console.log(typeof value); // "string"

// Cast the value to a string
value = value as string;
console.log(typeof value); // "string"
```

This ensures that the type system treats `value` as a `string` even though it is technically a union type.

